"{\"uid\": \"abc.net.au-news-2024-07-26-paris-olympics-horses-travel-overseas-104145584\", \"text\": \"Personalise the news and  stay in the know  Emergency  Backstory  Newsletters  \\u4e2d\\u6587\\u65b0\\u95fb  BERITA BAHASA INDONESIA  TOK PISIN  Find any issues using dark mode?Please let us know  By Isabella Michie  By Craig Reucassel  ABC Radio Sydney  Topic:Olympic Games  The horses travelling from Australia to the 2024 Olympic Games will fly for more than 30 hours.(Supplied: Chris Burke, IRT)  Australian horses have flown to Paris in an air-stable to compete in the 2024 Olympic Games.  The horses require a passport before travelling.  When they land, the horses are monitored by their team for jet lag symptoms.  The Olympic Games are underway in Paris and Team Australia has settled into the Athlete's Village, including those competing in the equestrian events.  But how do their four-legged companions make their way to the French capital?  Chris Burke, the Managing Director of IRT, facilitates the international travel of horses and has transported three horses to the Olympics and one to the Paralympics.  Horses have passports that include their travel and vaccine history.(Supplied: Chris Burke, IRT)  To travel internationally humans must have a passport and horses are no different.  For the horses competing in the Olympics, their passport is issued by the International Federation for Equestrian Sports.  This document includes what vaccinations the horses have received and their travel history.  Horses do not have photos in their passports. Instead, there is a silhouette that has an outline and any unique markings or colours to help identify the horse, says Mr Burke.  \\\"But the main feature that identifies horses these days, like most animals is microchips,\\\" he says.  \\\"That is definitely in the passport.\\\"  The horses must not be given too much room in case of turbulence, but travel comfortably in the air stable.(Supplied: Chris Burke, IRT)  The horses travel in an air stable. They board using a high loader, which is similar to a scissor lift used to load passenger luggage.  The air stable is fully enclosed, with partitions separating the horses and a breast bar across the front to restrict the animals from moving forward.  ABC Sportis live blogging every day of the Paris Olympics  ABC Sportis live blogging every day of the Paris Olympics  Unfortunately, there are no in-flight movies for these passengers, but they do get a tasty barrel of hay.  \\\"They actually travel quite comfortably,\\\" Mr Burke said.  The horses stand up for the entire flight on their journey, which can sometimes lead to swelling.  Compression socks can be useful for humans who experience swelling during air travel, but it is not the same for horses.  It is not recommended to wrap the horse's legs as this can damage the tendons, Mr Burke said.  The opening ceremony for the 2024 Olympic Games, held almost entirely along Paris's River Seine, promises to be the most spectacular ever attempted - but it brings with it many complications and immeasurable risk.  The horses are well cared for during their journey, with Equestrian Australia providing a vet on the plane to monitor the horse's wellbeing throughout the flight.  With more than 30 hours of flying - including stopovers in Vietnam and Qatar - the journey to Paris would leave any human jet-lagged. But is it the same for horses?  \\\"We do not truly know the answer,\\\" Mr Burke said.  It is only in the first 24 - 48 hours after they have arrived that the impacts of the journey can be seen on the horses.  This is why the handlers arrive ahead of time, so they are fresh to care for the horses when they land, according to Mr Burke.  While there are no in-flight movies for the horses, they do get a barrel of hay to keep them entertained during the flight.(Supplied: Chris Burke, IRT)  Local horses definitely have an advantage, says Mr Burke.  \\\"It makes the efforts when Australia does well overseas all that better,\\\" he said.  \\\"These guys have to travel to the other side of the world, so the Australian team well and truly have the hardest run.\\\"  For this reason, some horses are sent to Europe for a year or two before the Olympics where they can adjust to the high level of competing.  Topic:Cricket  Topic:Cricket  Topic:Courts  Topic:NRL  Topic:NRL  Topic:Domestic Violence  Topic:Social Media  Topic:Federal Government  Topic:War  Topic:Royalty  Topic:Sport  Topic:Explainer  Animals  Olympic Games  Sport  Sydney  Topic:Domestic Violence  Topic:Social Media  Topic:Federal Government  Topic:War  Topic:Royalty  Topic:Rural and Remote Communities  Topic:Pollution  Topic:Geography  Topic:Royalty  We acknowledge Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples as the First Australians and Traditional Custodians of the lands where we live, learn, and work.  This service may include material from Agence France-Presse (AFP), APTN, Reuters, AAP, CNN and the BBC World Service which is copyright and cannot be reproduced.  AEST= Australian Eastern Standard Time which is 10 hours ahead of GMT (Greenwich Mean Time)\"}"